I made this recipe for a holiday brunch and it was awesome. Everyone was asking for the recipe. I did make a few minor changes to the recipe and cooking time. I sliced all of the potatoes with my mandolin. I layered the casserole with one layer of yukon and then one layer of sweet potato and then so on&. I substituted swiss cheese for the gruyere and added more herbs (I did use dried instead of fresh and herbs de provence instead of rosemary). I made the dish the night before and then let it sit out for about 45 minutes before I baked it. I did end up baking it for about 90 minutes; I kept it covered for an hour and then took the foil off. The only suggestion that I would have would be to lessen the amount of butter. It did seem a little greasy. I am going to make this again for Christmas.

Rating: 3
I made this as a test to see if I wanted to make it for Christmas Eve. It is delicious, but very rich, so I'll only make it for special occasions. The liquid didn't absorb fully, so next time I'll use at least 2 cups of cheese, and cook for about 20 minutes longer. I ended up transferring it to a casserole dish and adding a bit of flour. It didn't look as pretty, but the consistency was much better, and taste wasn't compromised. I'll probably add about 1-2 tbsp of flour to the cream next time. Also next time I'll slice the sweet potatoes slightly thicker, as they were quite soft while the yukons were firm. I'll definitely make again.

